---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const components = [
  {
    label: "cmd/bore + internal/client/",
    title: "P2P transfer engine",
    description:
      "Rendezvous, STUN discovery, candidate signaling, direct transport, relay fallback, crypto, and file integrity.",
  },
  {
    label: "cmd/relay + internal/relay/",
    title: "Signaling server + fallback transport",
    description:
      "Coordinates direct-connection setup, relays encrypted frames when direct fails, and exposes operator endpoints.",
  },
  {
    label: "cmd/bore-admin",
    title: "CLI operator summary",
    description:
      "Polls /status over HTTP for a terse terminal-side view of relay uptime, room counts, and transport activity.",
  },
  {
    label: "cmd/punchthrough + internal/punchthrough/",
    title: "NAT traversal engine",
    description:
      "STUN probing, NAT classification, and UDP hole-punching integrated into the default transfer path.",
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="bore | peer-to-peer encrypted transfer"
  description="Direct file transfer with a short rendezvous code, end-to-end encryption, and relay fallback when direct peer-to-peer fails."
>
  <section class="hero panel panel--hero">
    <div class="hero__copy">
      <p class="eyebrow">Peer-to-peer. Encrypted. Self-hostable.</p>
      <h1>Direct file transfer with no one in the middle.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        bore moves a file between two machines with a short rendezvous code and a
        Noise handshake. The default path is direct peer-to-peer via STUN discovery,
        candidate exchange, and UDP hole-punching. When direct fails, the relay
        forwards encrypted bytes as a transparent fallback without seeing plaintext.
      </p>
      <div class="hero__actions">
        <a class="button button--solid" href="/ops/relay">Open relay operator surface</a>
        <a class="button button--ghost" href="#current-shape">See current shape</a>
      </div>
      <ul class="facts-list">
        <li>No accounts, no cloud mailbox, no payload inspection.</li>
        <li>Default transport is direct P2P. Relay is the automatic fallback.</li>
        <li>The browser surface stays read-only and same-origin to the Go relay.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="hero__panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Rendezvous code example</p>
      <code class="code-sample">Ahcj7nQZclo-j15A_xGS8w-868-outer-crane-crane</code>
      <dl class="spec-grid">
        <div>
          <dt>Handshake</dt>
          <dd>Noise XXpsk0</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Channel</dt>
          <dd>ChaCha20-Poly1305</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Integrity</dt>
          <dd>SHA-256</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt>Default path</dt>
          <dd>direct P2P</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="two-up" id="current-shape">
    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">Current shipped path</p>
      <h2>P2P first, relay fallback, claims kept tight.</h2>
      <p>
        The client in <code>cmd/bore</code> discovers each peer's public address via
        STUN, exchanges candidates through the relay signaling channel, and attempts a
        direct UDP connection via hole-punching. If direct fails, the transfer falls
        back to the relay automatically.
      </p>
      <p>
        The relay in <code>cmd/relay</code> serves two narrow roles: signaling server
        for peer connection setup, and fallback transport for encrypted byte
        forwarding. It never sees plaintext regardless of which path is used.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="panel">
      <p class="eyebrow">What the browser surface is for</p>
      <h2>A product face plus a practical operator page.</h2>
      <p>
        bore serves the homepage at <code>/</code> and a read-only relay status page at
        <code>/ops/relay</code>. The browser view stays deliberately thin so it does not
        grow into a hidden control plane.
      </p>
      <p>
        Live operator data comes from the relay's Go-owned <code>/status</code> contract.
        The same payload also powers <code>bore-admin status</code>.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="panel">
    <p class="eyebrow">Transfer lane</p>
    <h2>How the secure path works today.</h2>
    <ol class="step-list">
      <li>Sender creates a relay room and receives a full rendezvous code.</li>
      <li>Each peer discovers its public address via STUN and exchanges candidates through the relay.</li>
      <li>Peers attempt a direct UDP connection via hole-punching.</li>
      <li>Both peers mix the rendezvous code into a Noise XXpsk0 handshake over the established connection.</li>
      <li>Encrypted file frames flow directly between peers, or via relay if direct failed.</li>
      <li>Receiver verifies the final SHA-256 digest before accepting the file.</li>
    </ol>
    <p class="panel__footnote">
      If the direct connection fails at any step, the transfer falls back to the relay
      automatically. Use <code>--relay-only</code> to skip the direct attempt.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="component-grid">
    {
      components.map((component) => (
        <article class="panel panel--compact">
          <p class="eyebrow">{component.label}</p>
          <h3>{component.title}</h3>
          <p>{component.description}</p>
        </article>
      ))
    }
  </section>

  <section class="panel panel--cta">
    <p class="eyebrow">Operator surface</p>
    <h2>Need the live relay picture?</h2>
    <p>
      The relay operator page shows uptime, room counts, transport stats, and configured
      limits from the same <code>/status</code> endpoint that powers
      <code>bore-admin status</code>.
    </p>
    <a class="button button--solid" href="/ops/relay">Open relay status page</a>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
